defaultClimate models are unable to describe (resolve) 
defaultsome of 
defaultthe important processes
default which control the climate.   
defaultThe location
default of “blocking anticy
defaultclones”, high pressures in the Atlantic
default,
default largely determine the flux of warm moist air to the North Pole.  Climate models cannot resolve these large scale meteorological features, basically because the smaller scale eddies in the atmosphere, which drive and maintain these large structures, are to
defaulto small and cannot be seen or resolved by climate models.  Thus the transport of heat to the poles (the main kinematic function of the atmosphere on the global scale) is misrepresented.  The critical differences between the Northern Hemisphere circulation,
default where the frequency of
default “blocks” are under-represented 
defaultand the Southern Hemisphere circulation, where blocks are far to
defaulto frequent
default,
default is important.  This inadequacy 
defaultis of significant concern
default in the prediction of future climates
default.  The increase in intensity of 
defaultSouthern North Atlantic hurricanes
default, observed, understood and predicted by meteor
defaulto
defaultlogists, and which have significant impact o
defaultn the North American climate is
default not seen in climate models. The resolution in climate models is just not good enough to produce the
defaultm as they are driven from smaller scale convective systems and easterly waves, too small for these models.
